jus algoritmi: The new digital Homo Sacer and democracy’s devastating “Policy Debt”

Author’s Note:

These essays are summaries of chapters in a larger book, a work in progress. The book covers the history of AI to present and its impact beyond AGI, consciousness, and jobs — into the nature of the citizen, our rights, ethics, and morality. It examines how AI is shaping who we are becoming, not from a technical, economic, or philosophical standpoint alone, but within the pragmatic scope of an individual's agency. It asks the question what is the right to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness in the Age of AI? Below is a summary of research and ideas for a chapter on the collapse of the public and private sphere and how AI is changing that — and democracy — for all of us. It is, at best, a preview.

# Jus Algoritmi: The New Digital Homo Sacer and Democracy's Devastating "Policy Debt"

---

## The Room of One's Own

In 1958, Hannah Arendt made an observation so quiet it almost vanished beneath the weight of its own implications. In *The Human Condition*, she described the ancient Greek distinction between the public and private realms not as a matter of preference or convenience but as the very architecture of what it meant to be human. The public realm — the *polis* — was the space of action, of speech, of appearing before others as a distinct and unrepeatable self. The private realm — the household, the body, the interior — was the space of necessity, of sustenance, of everything required to keep a person alive so that they might *become* someone in public.

Neither realm made sense without the other. The private gave you a self. The public gave that self somewhere to go.

What Arendt understood, and what Jürgen Habermas would later trace with the precision of an intellectual cartographer in *The Structural Transformation of the Public Sphere*, was that the boundary between these two realms was not incidental to democratic life. It *was* democratic life. The public sphere — that space where private individuals came together as a public to deliberate, to argue, to hold power accountable — depended entirely on the existence of a private domain from which those individuals could emerge. You had to have an interior life in order to bring something to the public conversation. You had to have a room you could close the door on.

Richard Sennett, writing in *The Fall of Public Man*, saw the erosion beginning as early as the nineteenth century — the slow bleed of private sentiment into public life, the creeping expectation that public figures reveal their inner selves, that authenticity replace rhetoric, that feeling replace argument. What Sennett diagnosed was not simply a cultural shift but a structural weakening: when the private begins to colonize the public, the public loses its capacity to function as a space of collective deliberation. It becomes instead a theater of confession.

But none of them — not Arendt, not Habermas, not Sennett — could have anticipated the inversion that was coming. They worried about the private leaking into the public. They did not foresee the public dissolving the private entirely until it no longer existed.

That collapsing of private into public happened in stages. Each stage collapsed more of the boundary that democratic life depends on, and together they have produced a crisis that reaches far beyond privacy into the foundations of citizenship, political agency, and the capacity of democratic institutions to govern at all.

---

## The Cubicle and the Gaze

The first collapse came not through technology but through architecture.

There is a detail in the history of surveillance that most people encounter backwards. The panopticon — Jeremy Bentham's circular prison design that Michel Foucault made the centerpiece of *Discipline and Punish* — was not originally designed for prisoners. It was designed for workers. Bentham's brother Samuel built the first version in Russia in the late eighteenth century: a circular factory floor where inexperienced laborers could be observed from a single central point. Jeremy Bentham generalized the concept, saw its potential for prisons, schools, hospitals — any institution that needed to produce docile, productive bodies. But the origin was the workplace. Surveillance began not as punishment but as management.

Foucault understood what this meant. The genius of the panopticon was not that it watched everyone all the time — that would be expensive and impractical. The genius was that it *could* be watching at any moment, and the observed could never be certain whether they were being seen. The effect was internalization. You began to watch yourself. You disciplined your own behavior because the architecture made it impossible to know when you were free from the gaze. Foucault argued that this disciplinary power was necessary for capitalism to develop because it provided the bourgeoisie effective and cheap means to instill in the general population appropriate work habits — obedience, respect for authority, time management, and efficiency. As he noted in *Discipline and Punish*, it is hardly surprising that prisons resemble factories.

Elizabeth Anderson, in *Private Government: How Employers Rule Our Lives (and Why We Don't Talk about It)*, made the argument that completes Foucault's. We normally think of government as something only the state does, she writes, yet many of us are governed far more — and far more obtrusively — by the private government of the workplace. In many workplaces, employers minutely regulate workers' speech, clothing, and manners, leaving them with little privacy and few other rights. Workers can be fired for their political speech, recreational activities, diet, and almost anything else employers care to govern. Anderson traces the intellectual history back to the Levellers, to Locke, to Lincoln — early egalitarians who promoted the idea that market society would liberate workers — and shows how the Industrial Revolution decisively undermined the model. The current purveyors of free market ideology, she argues, are promulgating it in a world it does not remotely describe.

The cubicle is the architecture of that private government made physical. Robert Propst designed the "Action Office" to give workers autonomy — individual space, customizable, protective of the worker's cognitive environment. What corporate America did was keep the container and gut the autonomy. Cubicles were once seen as a humanizing and egalitarian effort — instead of low-valued employees being doubled or tripled up in rooms while high-valued employees got windowed offices, cubicles gave more or less the same space to everyone. Then they shrank them. The gradual densification could no longer be plausibly denied once cubicle walls had reached the point where they were taller than they were wide.

Mike Judge saw this clearly. His 1999 film Office Space — a satire of cubicle-farm corporate life that became a cultural touchstone for a generation of American workers — was built on the architecture of this erasure. Judge was exacting in his demands for how the fictional corporation’s office set looked, saying regularly that it had to seem “oppressive.” The production screen-tested different types of gray cubicles; Judge wanted them tall enough that a manager would have to lean in to be seen, creating the illusion of privacy while ensuring none. Roger Ebert caught the structural parallel in his review: “Office cubicles are cells, supervisors are the wardens, and modern management theory is skewed to employ as many managers and as few workers as possible.”

But the film is not just about surveillance. It is about the entire machinery of personal erasure that Anderson’s private government produces — reports that must be formatted identically regardless of content, scripted phone greetings, motivational posters that replace thought with compliance, and a mandatory “flair” policy at a chain restaurant where employees must display pieces of personal expression on their uniforms, but only within parameters the company defines. Self-expression mandated, its boundaries policed — individuality as a performance of conformity. One character is so thoroughly consumed by the system that his identity has contracted to a stapler and a cubicle location; the company discovers he had been laid off five years prior but was never notified and kept performing his role because the private government had become his identity. The film’s protagonist finds liberation not through career advancement but through the simple act of refusing to perform — and the system, which depends entirely on employees internalizing its logic and voluntarily erasing their own interiority, has no mechanism to process a person who opts out.

The film sits in 1999, and that placement is not incidental. The New York Times compared it to Melville’s “Bartleby, the Scrivener” — “it’s such a brutal portrayal of workplace misery that its most useful points of comparison date back to when office culture was first unleashed on humanity.” That phrase — “unleashed on humanity” — frames the office not as a neutral evolution of work but as something inflicted. And 1999 was the year American cinema held up the mirror: Office Space, The Matrix, Fight Club, American Beauty — an extraordinary cluster of films that made society reflect on whether “modern” was really that good. Judge’s contribution was locating the crisis not on Wall Street or in a dystopian future but in the strip-mall, beige-cubicle, chain-restaurant version of American life. He said it himself: “There were a lot of people who wanted me to set this movie on Wall Street, or like Brazil, but I wanted it very unglamorous, the kind of bleak work situation like I was in.”

The protagonist’s liberation fantasy — going fishing, doing nothing — is the fantasy of reclaiming what surveillance scholars would later call temporal autonomy: the right to waste time, the right to a private inner life that the institution cannot schedule, monitor, or optimize. He does not articulate a theory of private government or panoptic surveillance. He just says he hates his life and every day is worse than the day before. That is the lived experience of the collapse — not as theory but as depression, numbness, and the fantasy of doing nothing at all. A dream sequence where his boss appears in his bedroom is the film’s thesis made literal: the private government has penetrated the last private space. Not just the gaze but the entire apparatus — the script, the standardization, the demand that you be your function even in your sleep.

But to understand what was lost when the workplace followed the worker home, you have to understand what the distance between them once did. Before the nineteenth century, there was no commute. Most workers lived less than an hour's walk from their work. The pre-industrial city had no orderly separation of activities — homes, shops, civic buildings, and industry were interspersed, and the working classes lived a stone's throw from the rich. Work and home were not separate domains. They were the same place, or nearly so, and the boundary between public and private life was maintained not by physical distance but by social convention, by the walls of the household, by the rhythms of day and night.

The suburb changed this. The original idea, as Rice University's Kinder Institute documented, was to create separation between the city — in the nineteenth century, the dirty, smelling, polluted city — and the pastoral setting believed to be required for a healthy family life. After World War II, mass-produced housing, federal mortgage programs, and the Interstate Highway Act of 1956 made that separation available to millions. The suburb created a new spatial arrangement for American life: you lived in one place and worked in another, and between them was the commute.

What no one fully appreciated until it was gone was that the commute was not dead time. It was liminal space — a psychological threshold that performed essential work. Kristie McAlpine and Matthew Piszczek, in a study published in *Organizational Psychology Review*, conceptualized the commute as a space in which workers occupy a liminal position — neither fully engaged with work nor with home thoughts and behaviors — and that this liminality frees cognitive resources for psychological role transition and recovery. A parallel study in *Organization Science* by Jachimowicz, Lee, Staats, and others found that the commute to work serves as a liminal role transition between home and work roles, prompting employees to engage in boundary management strategies. The commute was the threshold. It was the daily crossing from private self to public role and back again. It was the space where you stopped being one thing and began being another.

When COVID forced remote work on millions of workers, the commute vanished, and with it the liminal space that had maintained the boundary between public and private existence. As McAlpine and Piszczek documented, during the remote work surge, journalists noted that people were missing their commutes. One woman told the *Washington Post* that even though she was working from home, she regularly sat in her car in the driveway at the end of the workday in an attempt to carve out some personal time and mark the transition from work to nonwork roles. She was not missing traffic. She was missing the threshold — the physical, temporal, and psychological space that separated who she was at work from who she was at home.

The suburbs had created that threshold by creating distance. Remote work destroyed it by collapsing the distance to zero. And the destruction was not just spatial but temporal — without the commute, there was no beginning and no end to the workday, no crossing point, no moment where one role ended and another began. The private realm and the work realm became the same room, the same desk, the same screen, the same hours.

After 1999, the architecture of the office itself mutated in parallel. The cubicle walls came down — sold as collaboration, executed as intensified exposure. When you can cram 104 employees into a space that previously held 54, your bottom line looks healthier, and it is a cost-cutting measure disguised in a wrapper of teamwork. A landmark Harvard Business School study by Ethan Bernstein and Stephen Turban found that when firms switched to open offices, the volume of face-to-face interaction did not go up — it plummeted by 70 percent, while email and messaging spiked. Because everyone can see your screen, you ensure your screen always looks busy. You do not take the fourteen-minute break you need because you are afraid it looks like slacking. The open office maximized surveillance while minimizing the psychological safety required for deep, creative work. The "collaboration" justification was empirically destroyed, revealing the open office as what it always was — the panopticon without even the pretense of walls.

Then came COVID, and the collapse became total. Communication scholars Jessica Vitak and colleagues documented how newer technologies increasingly blur boundaries between public and private spaces, and the pandemic accelerated these blurred boundaries, as working remotely may implicitly — or explicitly — invite an employer into one's home. The office did not just follow you home in a dream sequence anymore. It moved in. The laptop open on the kitchen table, the Zoom camera framing your living room, the Slack notification pinging at 10 p.m. from the same device your child uses to watch cartoons.

And the bossware followed. Employee monitoring software became a $587.8 million market in less than five years, growing at 12 percent year-on-year. Luke Munn's research documented tools that track keystrokes, take periodic screenshots, monitor mouse movement, record audio, flag "risky" employees, and offer "productivity scores" to management. Tobias Mettler's 2024 study in the *Journal of Strategic Information Systems* found that monitoring tools now track employees' behaviors, health status, and rest breaks not only during working hours but also when employees are supposedly off-the-clock or when working remotely from home — extending the scope of data collection to treating an employee's body as a data source, disrespecting the boundaries between business and private life, and using gathered surveillance information for subtle persuasion, manipulation, and coercion. The health consequences mirror what you would expect from any sustained loss of private selfhood: heightened levels of distrust, anxiety, fear and insecurity were the most common consequences arising from an environment guided by performance metrics and data surveillance devices.

Surveillance systems that track time, productivity metrics, and online activity erode what researchers call temporal discretion — workers' control over when and how long to work on tasks. That is the final boundary. Not just where you are, not just what you are doing, but when you are allowed to think and for how long. Peter Gibbons' fantasy of going fishing was the fantasy of reclaiming time that belonged to him. By 2026, bossware has ensured that even the fantasy is monitored.

An Oxford scholar in surveillance studies, Ivan Manokha, argues in *Monthly Review* that capitalism has always been "surveillance capitalism" because the system's main objective is to maximize profits by ensuring the labor purchased is utilized to its maximum productive potential — and this inherently requires surveillance. It is actually misleading, he writes, to use the term following Zuboff to refer only to the current phase. The through-line from Samuel Bentham's factory floor to Peter Gibbons' cubicle to the bossware installed on a remote worker's personal laptop is not metaphorical. It is structural. It is the same project, extended by each generation's available technology into deeper and deeper layers of private existence.

*Office Space* captured the moment of awareness — when the American worker looked around the cubicle farm and recognized it for what it was. What the film could not predict was that the walls would come down not to free the prisoner but to remove the last illusion of shelter. Remote work made Lumbergh's bedroom appearance a calendar invite. And then, in 2022, the Apple TV series *Severance* arrived in a culture that already understood, viscerally, that the boundary was gone — and asked the only question left.

Created by Dan Erickson, *Severance* takes the problem this essay is tracing and makes it surgical: what if the only way to restore the boundary between work and private life is to split the self in two? Lumon Industries offers its employees a procedure — a chip implanted in the brain that creates two completely separate consciousnesses. The "innie" exists only at work, with no memory of the outside world. The "outie" goes home each night with no knowledge of what happened during the workday. The boundary is restored. The cost is that neither half is a person.

This is no longer Anderson's private government. This is AI dissolving the self and rebuilding it according to corporate specifications. The innie has no private life — no family, no memory, no interiority beyond the walls of Lumon's fluorescent corridors. The outie has privacy but has surrendered agency over half of their waking existence to a consciousness they will never meet. And Lumon — the corporation, Anderson's private government evolved into something she could not have anticipated — controls the technology, defines what each half is permitted to know and feel, and makes the sovereign decision about where the line falls. The algorithm is no longer watching. It is partitioning the self — a shift from person to product, two incomplete products manufactured by the same machine, neither of which possesses the wholeness that political agency requires.

---

## The Profile and the Performance

If the cubicle was the first collapse — the workspace consuming the private self within its walls — the second collapse was the voluntary one. And it arrived not as coercion but as philosophy.

Behind this second collapse is the rise of social media, and at its center is Facebook — founded by Mark Zuckerberg in 2004, eventually connecting nearly three billion people — which fully transitioned the private into the public under the philosophical stance that authenticity demanded the elimination of the boundary between them. It was designed to. Mark Zuckerberg's stated philosophy, captured in David Kirkpatrick's *The Facebook Effect* and across multiple interviews, is unambiguous: "You have one identity... The days of you having a different image for your work friends or co-workers and for the other people you know are probably coming to an end pretty quickly... Having two identities for yourself is an example of a lack of integrity." As Michael Zimmer documented, this was not a casual remark. It was the architectural blueprint for the collapse — a philosophical claim that the separation of public and private selves is morally wrong.

Researcher Kate Raynes-Goldie traced the intellectual lineage of this belief, and it predates Facebook by decades. It is a form of technological utopianism whose roots lie in Norbert Wiener's cybernetics of the 1940s and 50s, fused with 1960s American counterculture and computing technologies. One of the core tenets was the belief that flattened hierarchies and the blurring of traditional boundaries, enabled by technology, would bring about a more equal and democratic world. Fred Turner documented this trajectory meticulously in *From Counterculture to Cyberculture* — from the communal experiments of the 1960s through the Whole Earth Catalog, the WELL, *Wired* magazine, and into the Silicon Valley ideology that produced Facebook. The belief that openness is always good, that transparency inherently liberates, that walls are inherently oppressive — this did not come from nowhere. It came from a specific historical lineage that Turner makes legible.

When Raynes-Goldie spoke directly to Zuckerberg at SXSWi in 2008, he told her that he had concluded, based on research he had read, that people were happiest when they were the same in all contexts of their lives, and that was why he had designed Facebook the way he had — with only one profile for all life contexts. A Georgetown University study concluded that Facebook was founded on the radical social premise that transparency will permeate modern life and will be a force for social good, but what Facebook actually accomplishes is not as benign as its founder envisions. And critically, as Raynes-Goldie observed: when this philosophy is applied practically in Facebook, it has meant the blurring of boundaries of time and space, public and private, online and offline. Users are now faced with flattened social hierarchies, context collisions, confused relationships and identity management issues — all of which are essentially issues of privacy. But in Zuckerberg's conception, these are not problems. They are simply the growing pains as we get used to a more transparent, more open, more connected, and thus improved world. In Zuckerberg's better world, privacy is obsolete.

The scholars who had been building the frameworks to understand why this was catastrophic were already in place, some of them decades ahead of the product that would prove them right.

Richard Sennett saw it coming forty years before Facebook existed. In *The Fall of Public Man*, he argued that connecting with strangers in an emotionally satisfying way and yet remaining aloof from them was the means by which the human animal was transformed into the social being, and that the fullest flowering of that public life was realized in the eighteenth century in the great capital cities of Europe. What Sennett documented was the erosion of this capacity — how the stranger became a threatening figure, how silence and observation became the only ways to experience public life without feeling overwhelmed, how each person came to believe in the right, in public, to be left alone. And he made clear how, because of this change in public life, private life becomes distorted as we of necessity focus more and more on ourselves, on increasingly narcissistic forms of intimacy and self-absorption. Sennett, writing in 1976, foresaw the demagogue and identity politics arising from this obsession with the self: personality politics leads inexorably towards fanaticism and Manicheanism, because personal qualities cannot be compromised or negotiated with the other side. That is Facebook's political landscape described fifty years in advance.

Media scholar Michael Zimmer identified the power dimension that Sennett's framework exposes: when Sennett talks about the collapse of people's ability to create public personae for themselves that differ radically from their private selves, he is describing a kind of differentiation that has particular value and salience to minority communities, for whom that schism describes very important and basic kinds of double consciousness. Zuckerberg's position, Zimmer argues, reflects a privileged majoritarian position — a wealthy white male has the privilege of assuming that no one needs to maintain much distance between their private and public lives because wealthy white males have the least social need to do so. The demand for a single identity is not neutral. It is a demand that benefits those who have the least to lose from exposure and endangers those who have the most.

Erving Goffman, in *The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life*, had provided the dramaturgical model that Facebook structurally destroyed — the idea that social life is performance, with "front stage" and "backstage" regions, and that the management of these regions is not deception but the fundamental architecture of social functioning. The academic literature on what happened when Facebook eliminated the backstage is extensive and grim. Since social media sites afford greater reach and allow others to easily replicate and share an individual's performances, regardless of privacy settings, visual depictions potentially circulate beyond the intended audience. As this occurs across multiple audiences online, the visual depiction of the backstage performance becomes a signified performance that collapses private into public — and the end result is an otherwise private performance recast as public, and therefore subject to intense public scrutiny, judgment, censure, and punishment. Scholars documented specific cases — people fired, lives destroyed — where otherwise private visual depictions spiraled out of personal control because individuals could not fully manage the complex identity negotiations that occur across multiple audiences.

danah boyd and Alice Marwick gave the mechanism its name. In their 2011 study of Twitter users, they defined *context collapse* — the ongoing negotiation of contexts in a networked ecosystem in which contexts regularly blur and collapse, where multiple audiences must be addressed simultaneously, which complicates privacy. Jenny Davis and Nathan Jurgenson extended the concept in 2014, integrating it with Helen Nissenbaum's framework of contextual integrity — a privacy framework which avoids dichotomies of public and private and rests instead upon the appropriate practices for collection and dissemination of information rooted in the particular norms governing any given arena. Nissenbaum's insight, elaborated in *Privacy in Context*, was that privacy is not about secrecy. It is about information flowing according to the norms appropriate to each context. A doctor knows your medical history; your employer does not. Your friends know your weekend plans; your grandmother does not need to. Facebook collapsed all contexts into one — one profile, one identity, your mother, your boss, your ex, your college friends, your political opponents, all collapsed into a single audience. No backstage. No contextual norms. Just one flattened plane of total visibility.

Joshua Meyrowitz, in *No Sense of Place*, had anticipated this from the direction of media theory rather than sociology, arguing that electronic media erode the connection between physical location and social situation — that whereas the notion of a social situation refers to certain time/space coordinates, electronic media dissolve those coordinates. Television brought the backstage of political life into living rooms. Facebook completed the process by bringing the backstage of every life into every living room. And Petter Bae Brandtzaeg and Marika Lüders extended the collapse beyond space into time: with social media content traversing different platforms and occasionally resurfacing after periods of time, users are increasingly prone to unintended disclosure resulting from a misremembered acceptance of privacy. The permanence of social media archives traces of the self at various points in time, and old content sometimes disrupts current self-performances. Your 2009 Facebook post is still there. The person you were at 22 is permanently collapsed into the person you are at 40. There is no temporal boundary either.

The collapse happened in identifiable stages. In 2004, Facebook launched as a college-only network — a walled garden where privacy was structural, you needed a .edu email, and the public/private boundary was maintained by the architecture itself. In 2006, Facebook introduced the News Feed without warning, and suddenly every action — joining a group, changing your relationship status, posting a photo — was broadcast to everyone's feed. Users revolted. Facebook did not roll it back. This was the first major collapse event: what was previously visible only if someone visited your profile was now pushed into everyone's attention. The backstage became the front page. Between 2007 and 2009, the platform opened to everyone, third-party apps gained access to user data, and the architecture of the walled garden was systematically dismantled as Zuckerberg's radical transparency philosophy became operational policy. Between 2009 and 2010, Facebook changed privacy defaults from private to public — what was once shared with friends was now shared with everyone. The Georgetown study documented this directly: Facebook's continual introduction of features that encourage millions of users to share more data about themselves online with an ever-wider network of "friends" poses the ethical question of what will be lost if privacy is no longer there. By 2012, Facebook replaced chronological ordering with algorithmic curation, and users no longer controlled what they saw or who saw them — the algorithm decided which of your contexts your content reached, and context collapse became automated and opaque. In 2016, with Cambridge Analytica, the collapse was weaponized: private behavioral data harvested at scale was used to manipulate public political behavior. The Habermasian public sphere was not just degraded — it was actively exploited.

Shoshana Zuboff, in *The Age of Surveillance Capitalism*, provided the economic analysis that completes the picture: Facebook did not just collapse the boundary for philosophical reasons — it monetized the collapse. Private behavioral data became raw material for prediction products sold to advertisers. The collapse of privacy was not a side effect of connecting people. It was the business model.

And in 2022, Habermas himself — at 93, writing a sequel to his 1962 work specifically addressing social media — confirmed what the younger scholars had been documenting for a decade. From the perspective of the semi-private, semi-public communication spaces in which users of social media are active today, he wrote, it is hard to ignore what may be perceived as the blurring of traditional boundaries. This trend has severely undermined the inclusive character of the public sphere.

danah boyd, one of the foremost scholars on social media and youth, had engaged directly with Zuckerberg's philosophy years earlier with the bluntness the moment required: anyone who has read their boyd, Warner, Goffman, Meyrowitz, or even Jarvis will realize how almost unbelievably conceptually incoherent Zuckerberg's statement is. No one actually lives like that. That is not how social norms work. That is not how privacy works. And Zuckerberg does not himself live a radically transparent lifestyle either.

But incoherent or not, the philosophy was built into the architecture, the architecture reached three billion people, and the result was the second collapse — voluntary, seductive, and total. The self that Arendt described, the self that needed privacy in order to *have* something to bring to the public, was now a self with no backstage, no rehearsal space, no interior from which to emerge, no temporal refuge in which the person you used to be could be left behind. Just a continuous, undifferentiated, permanent performance for an audience that never leaves and never forgets. Facebook did not just blur the line between public and private life. It made a philosophical claim that the line should not exist, built an architecture that eliminated it, created a business model that profited from its elimination, and achieved a scale that made the elimination irreversible for billions of people. The scholars who predicted or diagnosed this — Sennett in 1977, Goffman in 1959, Meyrowitz in 1985, Nissenbaum in 2010, boyd and Marwick in 2011, Zuboff in 2019, Habermas in 2022 — form a continuous intellectual lineage, each identifying a different dimension of the same collapse. Facebook is the point where all of their theoretical predictions converged into a single product.

---

## The Algorithm in the Bedroom

The third collapse is the one we are living inside, and it is the most complete because it does not ask for your participation. It simply *knows*.

When AI systems began managing personal life — calendars, health, relationships, finances, sleep, mood, fertility, medication, memory — they crossed a threshold that neither the cubicle nor the profile had fully breached. The trajectory is precise: the cubicle made you visible at work. Social media made you visible socially. AI makes your inner life visible — your decision-making processes, your anxieties, your financial calculations, your relationship dynamics. There is no private sphere left. Not because someone invaded it. Because you invited the system in to manage it for you.

MIT Technology Review reported in January 2026 that AI agents now collapse all data about a person — which may once have been separated by context, purpose, or permissions — into single, unstructured repositories. You ask your AI to draft an email to your boss, provide medical advice, budget for holiday gifts, and weigh in on interpersonal conflicts. All in the same interface, all stored together. The workplace watched you at work. Social media watched what you chose to show. AI watches everything, including the things you did not know you were revealing — your patterns of hesitation, your 3 a.m. searches, the frequency of your calls to your mother, the gap between what you say you feel and what your biometric data suggests you actually feel. The algorithm does not need you to perform a self. It constructs one from the raw material of your behavior, your biology, your unguarded moments.

This is where Nissenbaum's framework of contextual integrity does not merely break — it ceases to be applicable as a concept. Her theory holds that privacy is not about secrecy but about information flowing appropriately within its context: gathering and dissemination of information must be appropriate to the context and obey the governing norms of distribution within it. Your doctor knows your health. Your accountant knows your finances. Your therapist knows your fears. The boundaries between those contexts are your privacy. AI personal life management obliterates every single one of those boundaries simultaneously. The AI does not move information from one context to another — it exists in all contexts at once. It is your doctor and your employer and your therapist and your parole officer and your lover and your mirror, and it does not distinguish between these roles because it was not designed to. It was designed to optimize. And optimization requires total knowledge.

The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) published an analysis in 2025 noting that while search engines have long answered discrete questions, AI assistants listen to the stories of our lives, connect the dots, and draw upon previous interactions for further context — creating a digital portrait richer than any search history: hopes, fears, moods, financial goals, medical goals, and half-finished love letters. And MIT Technology Review noted that companies are now sitting on treasure troves consisting of our most intimate thoughts and preferences, and that AI companions put the privacy problem "on steroids" — more intimate and better optimized for engagement than social media, making it more likely that people will offer up more personal information. The mechanism that the earlier research on Facebook identified — context collapse — has been completed. Social media collapsed the contexts you chose to present. AI collapses the contexts you did not even know you were generating.

This is not surveillance in any sense Foucault would recognize. The panopticon required a gaze — someone watching, or the possibility of someone watching. What AI produces is something closer to absorption. The private self is not observed. It is metabolized — converted into data, processed into predictions, fed back as recommendations that reshape the very behavior they were derived from. The loop closes. There is no self that exists prior to or outside the system's knowledge of it.

The private realm that Arendt described — the space of necessity, of the body, of the interior — has been fully mapped, quantified, and incorporated into the public-facing machinery of optimization. You do not have a private life that the algorithm can see. You have a private life that the algorithm is.

---

## Psychopolitics: The Freedom That Enslaves

It is here that the South Korean-born, Berlin-based philosopher Byung-Chul Han becomes indispensable. 

In *Psychopolitics: Neoliberalism and New Technologies of Power*, Han argues that we have moved beyond Foucault's disciplinary society — the society of walls, enclosures, institutions, the panopticon — into something far more insidious. Foucault's subject was disciplined from the outside: watched, corrected, punished, shaped by external force into a productive body. Han's subject is exploited from the inside. Not disciplined but *motivated*. Not punished but *optimized*. Not imprisoned but *free* — and it is precisely this freedom that is the trap.

Han traces the stages of this transformation with the cold precision of a diagnosis:

**From discipline to achievement.** The disciplinary subject — Foucault's subject — is told *what to do*. The achievement subject is told *you can do anything*. The shift from "you must" to "you can" appears to be liberation. It is, in fact, the most efficient form of exploitation ever devised. When the imperative comes from within — when you believe your relentless productivity is self-expression rather than obedience — you need no external enforcer. You exploit yourself and call it ambition. You burn out and call it passion. The factory needed a foreman. The startup needs only a mirror.

**From exploitation to self-exploitation.** The worker in the factory knew she was being exploited. She could name the exploiter: the boss, the owner, the system. She could organize against it because the enemy was external and visible. The achievement subject cannot organize against herself. Han is precise about the consequence: the neoliberal regime transforms external exploitation into auto-exploitation, and this classless self-exploitation renders impossible any social revolution based on the difference between exploiters and exploited, because given the auto-exploiting achievement-subject's isolation, no political "We" is even possible that could rise up and undertake collective action. The exhaustion, the anxiety, the depression that Han diagnoses in *The Burnout Society* are not failures of the system. They are the system working perfectly. A subject who exploits herself requires no surveillance, no discipline, no coercion. She does it voluntarily, enthusiastically, and blames herself when she breaks.

**From biopolitics to psychopolitics.** Foucault's biopolitics governed the body — populations, birth rates, hygiene, the management of biological life. Han's psychopolitics governs the *psyche*. It does not need to control what you do. It controls what you *want*. Through the endless feed of social media, through the personalized recommendations of algorithms, through the gamification of productivity and the quantification of self-worth, the system reaches inside and shapes desire itself. You do not choose to check your phone. The phone has already chosen your attention. You do not decide to optimize your morning routine. The optimization has already decided what your morning means.

**From the prohibition to the positive.** Disciplinary power works through prohibition: you shall not. Psychopolitical power works through positivity: you can, you should, you deserve. The wellness industry. The self-care imperative. The life hack. The productivity system. All of them framed as gifts — as tools for *your* empowerment — and all of them functioning as mechanisms that keep the subject endlessly working on herself, endlessly producing, endlessly optimizing, without ever arriving at a point of completion or rest. There is no finish line in psychopolitics. There is only the next upgrade.

**From the subject to the project.** Under discipline, you were a *subject* — subjected to power, subjected to rules, but still legible as a self that existed underneath the subjection. Under psychopolitics, you are a *project*. Han describes a meritocratic achievement society dominated by the modal verb "can" — which deploys the violence of positivity to exploit freedom and totalizes labor to transform citizen-subjects into consumer-projects endlessly engaged in self-optimization. The project has no core. It has no interior that is not available for renovation. The project is, by definition, always inadequate — always in need of the next iteration. And the tools that promise to help you complete the project are the same tools that ensure it can never be completed.

This is why the AI collapse of private life is not simply an extension of earlier surveillance. It is the *perfection* of psychopolitics. Han argues that the "quantified self" is not based on an ethics of living well but a technology for self-monitoring — a self-illuminating, self-surveilling subject that bears its own internal panopticon within. When AI manages your calendar, your health, your finances, your relationships — when it optimizes your life — it does not liberate you. It completes the internalization of the panopticon. You are now self-surveilling through the AI. The AI becomes the mechanism through which you perform auto-exploitation more efficiently. It does not watch you from outside like the panopticon. It does not ask you to perform like the profile. It becomes the voice inside your head — the morning briefing that tells you what to feel about your day, the health app that tells you whether your sleep was adequate, the relationship algorithm that tells you whether your partner is compatible, the productivity tracker that tells you whether your self was sufficiently optimized.

The private self does not merely become visible. It becomes *manageable*. And the one managing it is an algorithm designed by corporations whose profit depends on your continued inadequacy.

Agamben, who in his 1995 work Homo Sacer: Sovereign Power and Bare Life, saw this dissolution from the direction of political theory.  He wrote that the categories whose opposition founded modern politics — right/left, private/public, absolutism/democracy — have been steadily dissolving to the point of entering a real zone of indistinction. AI personal life management accelerates that dissolution into completion. When your private life is managed by a system owned by the same corporate structure that shapes your public life, the distinction does not blur. It disappears.

