## Homo Sacer: The Man Without a Country

In Homo Sacer,  Agamben describes a figure from Roman law:  describes a figure from Roman law: the *homo sacer*, the sacred man, who could be killed by anyone but could not be sacrificed. He existed outside the law — not as a criminal, who is still defined by the law that condemns him, but as a person who has been placed beyond the threshold of legal and political existence altogether. He is not punished. He is simply *excluded*. He has biological life — *zoē*, bare life, the life of the body — but he has no political life, no *bios*, no standing in the community as a speaking, acting, rights-bearing citizen.

Agamben argued that the production of bare life — the reduction of the person to the biological, the stripping away of political standing — is not an aberration of sovereign power but its fundamental operation. The sovereign is the one who decides who is inside and who is outside. The sovereign draws the line between the citizen and the homo sacer.

What we are witnessing now is the production of homo sacer by algorithmic means.

A recent paper published on ResearchGate interprets artificial intelligence as a theological event: the reappearance of sovereignty through technological transcendence, where the algorithm emerges as a new Leviathan — invisible, non-human, and yet absolute — capable of deciding exceptions, allocating life, and determining truth through recursive computation rather than deliberation. The sovereign, in Agamben's framework, is the one who decides the exception — who is inside the law and who is outside it. The algorithm now makes that decision thousands of times per second, and it does so without deliberation, without appeal, without recognition that the decision is sovereign at all.

John Cheney-Lippold named the mechanism *jus algoritmi* — the right of the algorithm. Where *jus soli* grants citizenship by soil and *jus sanguinis* by blood, *jus algoritmi* determines your political and social existence by data. And Cheney-Lippold identified the feature that makes algorithmic citizenship uniquely devastating: it is constantly in flux. Moment by moment, the citizenship assigned to us, and thus the rights we may claim and the laws we are subject to, are changing. We have become effectively stateless, as the concrete rights we have been accustomed to flicker and shift. The algorithm decides who you are — your creditworthiness, your risk profile, your employability, your eligibility for services, your visibility in search results, your capacity to participate in the digital public sphere that has replaced the physical one. And its decisions are, for most practical purposes, sovereign. They are not subject to appeal in any meaningful sense. They are not transparent. They are not accountable to the person they define.

A 2025 study published in ResearchGate under the title "Digital Exile" documented the human rights implications of what the researchers called algorithmic suppression — the capacity of platforms to effectively erase a person from public existence without any legal proceeding, without any formal accusation, without any of the protections that even the most authoritarian states nominally provide. You are not arrested. You are not charged. You are simply *removed* — from the platform, from the search results, from the digital infrastructure that now constitutes the public sphere. You technically retain your rights. You technically retain your citizenship. But you have no functional capacity to exercise either.

Igor Calzada, writing in *Citizenship Studies* in 2021, described the emergence of what he called digital citizenship regimes — new forms of belonging and exclusion that operate alongside and increasingly *override* traditional nation-state citizenship. You can hold a passport and still be, in every practical sense, stateless — if the algorithmic systems that mediate access to employment, housing, healthcare, communication, and community have designated you as a non-entity.

Research on shadow banning and algorithmic suppression has documented what this looks like from the inside. Prolonged and inescapable exclusion leads to what researchers describe as a "resignation stage" — the individual's psychological resources are depleted, producing alienation, depression, helplessness, and unworthiness. The researchers call it a form of "social death," where victims are exiled from their digital communities by the invisible hand of an inscrutable algorithm. You are not formally banished. You are simply made invisible — your posts unseen, your voice unheard, your existence functionally erased from the spaces where social and economic life now takes place.

And this is not theoretical. In a summer 2025 article, TechCrunch reported that Meta’s automated systems suspended Manya Khurana’s Instagram account. Khurana had maintained the account since 2017, built a following of nearly 12,000, and was preparing to launch her small business on the platform. When she tried to appeal, agents were dismissive and closed chats without resolution. Meta’s Communications Director declined to comment. In what Khurana called a “heartbreaking” turn, she was unable to start her business. False accusations and AI mis-flags can remove a person from a service essential to their professional life, providing no transparent process and no meaningful appeal — making them, in effect, a digital homo sacer. They are within the system. They still have a body, a legal identity, a country of residence. But they have been stripped of the capacity to function as a political and economic subject. They are bare life in a digital sense — alive but rendered invisible, present but powerless. The sovereign decision was made not by a court or a legislature but by a content moderation algorithm and a terms-of-service clause that no one reads and everyone is bound by.

This is the technologically produced homo sacer. Not exiled by a sovereign's decree. Not stripped of citizenship by a court. Simply *processed* out of political existence by systems that were never designed to recognize political existence in the first place. The algorithm does not care about your rights. It does not know what rights are. It knows your data, your patterns, your risk score. And if your risk score falls below the threshold — or rises above it — you are outside.

The UNESCO report "Republic and Algorithm," published in 2025, framed this in explicitly political-philosophical terms: the algorithm functions as a new Leviathan — Hobbes' sovereign, the entity to which all have submitted their individual power in exchange for order. But this Leviathan was not chosen. This social contract was not signed. You did not consent to be governed by the algorithm. You simply woke up one day and discovered that it had been governing you all along — and that the government you thought you lived under had, in most of the ways that touch your daily life, been replaced by something that has no constitution, no electorate, and no obligation to recognize you as human.

---

## The Sovereign Algorithm and the Oligarchy of Intelligence

And so we arrive at the question that connects everything: who controls the algorithm?

The answer is not the state. It is not the people. It is not the democratic institutions that nominally govern public life. It is a small number of corporations — an oligarchy in the precise, classical sense — that build, train, deploy, and profit from the AI systems that now mediate the collapse of private life, shape the psychopolitical landscape, and determine who achieves functional citizenship and who becomes homo sacer.

This is not conspiracy. It is structure. The concentration of AI development in a handful of companies — and the concentration of the computational resources, training data, and talent required for that development in an even smaller handful — produces a power arrangement that is oligarchic by definition. Not because these companies intend to rule, but because the systems they build *do* rule, and the systems they build are controlled by them.

The Pentagon's dispute with Anthropic in early 2026 illuminated this with uncomfortable clarity. When a single AI company could refuse the Department of Defense's terms — and when the government's response was to classify that company as a "supply chain risk" and redirect its contracts to a competitor — the power dynamic was laid bare. The state does not control AI. The state *negotiates* with AI companies, and when negotiation fails, the state retaliates with the only tools it has: procurement leverage and regulatory threat. But the underlying capacity — the technology itself, the models, the data, the infrastructure — remains in private hands.

And this oligarchy controls precisely the machinery we have been describing. The AI systems that absorb private life? Built by these companies. The psychopolitical tools of self-optimization? Deployed on their platforms. The algorithmic gatekeeping that produces digital homo sacer? Operated by their models, trained on their data, governed by their policies. The sovereign decision — who is inside, who is outside, who exists as a functional citizen and who is processed into bare life — is made not by elected officials or democratic institutions but by corporate policies, content moderation algorithms, risk assessment models, and terms of service that no one reads and everyone is bound by.

The algorithm is the new sovereign. And the oligarchy is the hand on the switch.

---

## Policy Debt: Legislating for a Ghost

There is a concept in software engineering called *technical debt* — the accumulated cost of shortcuts taken during development that must eventually be repaid, usually at compound interest, usually at the worst possible moment. Every quick fix that defers a proper solution adds to the debt. Eventually, the system becomes so encumbered by its own accumulated shortcuts that it can no longer function, and the cost of repair exceeds the cost of having done it correctly from the beginning.

What we are witnessing in the relationship between democratic governance and the technological restructuring of human life is something analogous, and arguably more dangerous. Call it *policy debt*.

Policy debt is not simply regulatory lag — the familiar complaint that legislation cannot keep pace with technological change. Regulatory lag assumes that the object of regulation remains stable while the law catches up. Policy debt describes something more fundamental: the object of regulation — the citizen, the political subject, the self-governing individual on whom democratic theory depends — has been *structurally transformed* by the very technologies that policy is attempting to regulate. The law is not merely slow. It is writing rules for a person who no longer exists in the form the rules assume.

Every piece of privacy legislation that defines the individual as a person who *chooses* to share information is legislating for a ghost. The AI-mediated subject does not choose. She is *constituted* by the sharing — her identity, her preferences, her political orientation, her capacity for agency are produced by the data flows that privacy law imagines she controls. The law gives her the right to consent. But consent requires a self that exists prior to and independent of the systems requesting it. That self has been dissolved.

Every piece of antitrust regulation that imagines the market as a space where autonomous actors make free choices is legislating for a ghost. The psychopolitical subject does not choose freely. Her desires have been shaped, her attention has been captured, her sense of what is possible has been algorithmically curated. The market freedom that antitrust law protects is a freedom exercised by a subject who has been pre-optimized to exercise it in precisely the ways the optimizers prefer.

And yet — the vote remains. The right to draft and present policy to Congress remains. The citizen who has been algorithmically redefined, whose private deliberative space has been colonized by the feed, still holds the singular democratic instrument that the algorithm cannot cast on her behalf. This is not a ghost at a ballot box. This is a person who retains real power but operates within conditions designed to keep her from recognizing it, from stepping outside the algorithmic environment long enough to exercise it with full force. The gap is not one of capacity but of *conditions* — and closing that gap, reclaiming the deliberative space necessary to wield the tools that democracy still provides, is precisely where activism in the current moment finds its most critical foothold.

Each year that policy fails to account for the dissolution of the subject it governs, the gap widens between the legal fiction of the autonomous citizen and the lived reality of the algorithmically constituted project. And like technical debt, policy debt does not simply accumulate — it degrades the capacity of the system to function at all. A democracy that governs ghosts is not governing. It is performing governance while the actual decisions that shape human life are made elsewhere, by entities that owe no allegiance to the demos and recognize no obligation to the public sphere.

This is where the next chapter begins — with the question of what agency looks like when the subject of agency has been dissolved, and what politics becomes when the polis is populated by citizens who exist only in the legal imagination. The debt is coming due. And no one has begun to calculate the cost.

